The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 IBM boss in another recce

 OUR CORRESPONDENT

 New Delhi, June 5: IBM chairman and chief executive officer Samuel Palmisano will start his two-day visit to India tomorrow ? his fourth since May 2003.

 With the country fast turning into an IT hub, the worlds biggest computer services company is looking at finetuning its presence in various areas, including business process outsourcing, delivery services, research and software development. 

 The visit acknowledges Indias role as one of the fastest growing market for IBM and a crucial base for delivering services overseas.

 The IBM chief will address 10,000 employees in Bangalore where he will share the stage with President A.P.J. Abdul Kalam and Bharti chairman Sunil Mittal. 

 Around 6,500 IBM employees in other cities will look on through a satellite connection.

 There has been a huge growth in IBMs workforce in India since 2002 when it had 4,900 employees. The company employed 9,000 employees in 2003. 

 After acquiring Daksh in June 2004 (which added 6,000 people), the employee strength went up to 29,000 in 2004. With 38,500 employees in 2005, IBM is one of the largest multinational employers.

 The companys business in India grew 61 per cent in the first quarter of this year, 55 per cent in 2005 and 45 per cent the year before.

 IBM operates in 14 cities with a network of 2,500 business partners in 40 cities. IBM has established over 25 centres in India.

 Palmisano will also, for the first time, address investors here. 

 About 50 global financial analysts will be present for the briefing, which is customarily held in the US.




